.TH JTUTIL-TRACE 1 "April 2026" "JTFRAME" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
jtutil-trace \- compare VCD output against a MAME trace
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B jtutil trace
.RI [ flags ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBjtutil trace\fR
helps debug a simulation against MAME by comparing a register trace with a VCD
capture.
.PP
The default input files are:
.TP
.B debug.trace
Text trace generated from MAME.
.TP
.B debug.vcd
VCD file used for comparison.
.PP
Use
\fB--base-name\fR
to override those file names.
.PP
JTFRAME attempts to match MAME variables and VCD signals automatically.
If a signal is not matched, add it manually with the interactive
\fBalias\fR
command.
.PP
The comparison session is interactive, although a script can also be used.
Type
\fBhelp\fR
to list the commands.
Session commands are stored in
\fBtrace.ses\fR
and overwritten each time.
.PP
Comparison is paused while these signals are high:
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBalu_busy\fR:
the ALU is solving a long operation
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBstr_busy\fR:
a long string operation is in progress
.IP \[bu] 2
\fBstack_busy\fR:
stack-related long operations are in progress
.SH FLAGS
.TP
.BI "\-b, \-\-base-name " name
Use
\fB<name>.trace\fR
and
\fB<name>.vcd\fR
instead of
\fBdebug.trace\fR
and
\fBdebug.vcd\fR.
The default base name is
\fBdebug\fR.
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Show the short command help.
.TP
.BI "\-m, \-\-make " cpu
Create a MAME trace file for the given CPU.
.TP
.B \-v, \-\-verbose
Enable verbose output.
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR jtutil (1),
.BR jtutil-vcd (1)
